    13	---
    14	
    15	# Feature Catalog Examples - Live Catalog Walkthrough
    16	
    17	A section-by-section reading of a real, shipped feature catalog so a new catalog can be modeled on a proven layout instead of the abstract contract alone.
    18	
    19	---
    20	
    21	## 1. OVERVIEW
    22	
    23	The packet `SKILL.md` states the contract; this reference shows a working instance of its content model. Everything below is drawn from the live legacy catalog at `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/`, the largest maintained catalog in the repo. That tree keeps its underscore root until the repository content migration. New output uses the canonical hyphenated paths shown below.
    24	
    25	Read this alongside the two scaffolds in `../assets/feature-catalog/`. The templates give you the empty shape; this walkthrough shows the shape filled in well.
    26	
    27	---
    28	
    29	## 2. THE LIVE EXAMPLE
    30	
    31	Location: `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature-catalog/`
    32	
    33	Canonical emitted shape, using content drawn from the live example:
    34	
    35	```text
    36	feature-catalog/
    37	├── feature-catalog.md            # root inventory + navigation
    38	├── retrieval/                # ~17 per-feature files
    39	│   ├── unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md
    40	│   ├── semantic-and-lexical-search-memorysearch.md
    41	│   └── ...
    42	├── mutation/                 # memory-indexing-memorysave.md, ...
    43	├── discovery/                # health-diagnostics-memoryhealth.md, ...
    44	├── maintenance/
    45	└── ...                           # twenty-plus category folders
    46	```
    47	
    48	The catalog groups a large MCP surface into category folders, each holding one file per feature. The root `feature-catalog.md` is the only navigation surface and owns the section order; the folder names do not encode ordering. Both the category folders and the per-feature files use bare descriptive kebab-case slugs with no numeric prefix.
    49	
    50	---
    51	
    52	## 3. ROOT CATALOG ANATOMY
    53	
    54	The root `feature-catalog.md` opens with frontmatter carrying `title`, `description`, `trigger_phrases`, `last_updated`, and a 4-part `version`, then a short H1 intro that names what the system does today:
    55	
    56	```markdown
    57	# Spec Kit Memory: Feature Catalog
    58	
    59	This document is the current feature inventory for the Spec Kit Memory system.
    60	It describes live MCP tools, pipeline stages, verification surfaces, and the
    61	supporting workflow scripts that ship with the same skill package.
    62	```
    63	
    64	After the intro it uses numbered all-caps H2 sections — `## 1. OVERVIEW` first, then one H2 per category (`## 2. RETRIEVAL`, and so on). There is no Table of Contents and no `<!-- ANCHOR -->` navigation comment.
    65	
    66	Inside each category section, every feature is an H3 entry that stays deliberately thin — a `#### Description`, a `#### Current Reality`, and a `#### Source Files` callout that links to the per-feature file rather than inlining the source tables:
    67	
    68	```markdown
    69	### Unified context retrieval (memory_context)
    70	
    71	#### Description
    72	...
    73	
    74	#### Current Reality
    75	...
    76	
    77	#### Source Files
    78	See `retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md` for full
    79	implementation and test file listings.
    80	```
    81	
    82	The OVERVIEW section is where this catalog carries system-specific context (a command-surface contract table, coverage maps). That is fine — but note what it does *not* do: it never dumps exhaustive source-file tables or scenario matrices into the root. That depth lives one link away, in the per-feature file.
    83	
    84	---
    85	
    86	## 4. PER-FEATURE FILE ANATOMY
    87	
    88	The file `retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md` is a good model for a full feature entry. It shows all four required sections and the sub-heading rule in action.
    89	
    90	**Frontmatter** carries a stable `title`, a one-line `description`, five `trigger_phrases`, and a 4-part `version`. The `trigger_phrases` include the exact feature name plus natural-language alternates and the tool name:
    91	
    92	```yaml
    93	title: "Unified context retrieval (memory_context)"
    94	trigger_phrases:
    95	  - "unified context retrieval"
    96	  - "memory_context"
    97	  - "context orchestration"
    98	  - "intent-based retrieval routing"
    99	  - "auto-detect task intent"
   100	```
   101	
   102	**H1 and template marker** — the H1 repeats the feature name with the tool in parentheses, immediately followed by the catalog template marker:
   103	
   104	```markdown
   105	# Unified context retrieval (memory_context)
   106	
   107	<!-- sk-doc-template: skill_asset_feature_catalog -->
   108	```
   109	
   110	**`## 1. OVERVIEW`** opens with the one-line summary, then a plain-language paragraph describing the feature from the caller's perspective (a "smart librarian" analogy), not from the implementation.
   111	
   112	**`## 2. HOW IT WORKS`** is long — well over three paragraphs — so it is broken into H3 sub-headings for navigation: `### Entry Point & Routing`, `### Configuration`, `### Async & Safety`, `### Post-Action Behavior`. This is exactly the sub-heading rule the contract requires for long sections; a short feature would use plain prose instead.
   113	
   114	**`## 3. SOURCE FILES`** carries two tables. The `### Implementation` table uses `File | Layer | Role` columns (Handler / Lib / Formatter rows pointing at real `mcp-server/**` paths). The `### Validation And Tests` table uses `File | Type | Role` columns with `Automated test` rows pointing at real `*.vitest.ts` files.
   115	
   116	**`## 4. SOURCE METADATA`** closes with the group, the canonical catalog source (`feature-catalog.md`), the feature file path, and a `Related references` link to a neighboring feature in the same category:
   117	
   118	```markdown
   119	- Group: Retrieval
   120	- Canonical catalog source: `feature-catalog.md`
   121	- Feature file path: `retrieval/unified-context-retrieval-memorycontext.md`
   122	Related references:
   123	- [semantic-and-lexical-search-memorysearch.md](semantic-and-lexical-search-memorysearch.md) — Semantic and lexical search (memory_search)
   124	```
   125	
   126	---
   127	
   128	## 5. PATTERNS TO REUSE
   129	
   130	- Keep the root entry to Description / Current Reality / a Source Files link — resist inlining source tables at the root.
   131	- Put the tool or command name in the H1 parentheses whenever the feature maps to a named tool.
   132	- Make `trigger_phrases` lead with the exact feature name, then add alternates and the tool name.
   133	- Apply the H3 sub-heading rule only when `HOW IT WORKS` actually runs long; short features stay plain prose.
   134	- Point `Related references` at the immediately adjacent features so readers can navigate without returning to the root.
   135	- Reference real, stable source and test paths — the whole point of a per-feature file is that its claims are auditable.
   136	
   137	---
   138	
   139	## 6. RELATED RESOURCES
   140	
